\cf0 Let me check what alignment is actually happening in the texture. The aspect ratio matches between PNG (820\'d7802) and viewBox (3417\'d73342) \'97 both \uc0\u8776  1.0224 \'97 so dimensions/aspect aren't the issue. But let me look at where the actual paper content sits inside the PNG vs where the panel constants expect it.I've diagnosed the actual issue. It's a different problem than the PNG dimensions, and your instinct to lean on the SVG is right \'97 let me explain.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 What's actually wrong:
\f0\b0 \
The PNG is correctly sized. PNG is 820 \'d7 802 with aspect 1.0224; SVG viewBox is 3417 \'d7 3342 with aspect 1.0224. The texture loads in matching coordinates and pixel-aligns to the SVG. I confirmed the embedded base64 in your viewer is byte-identical to 
\f2\fs26 source/pieces/069.png
\f0\fs24 . Aspect and content are right.\
The real issue is 
\f1\b the panel rectangles extend outside the paper silhouette
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The PNG alpha channel splits cleanly: 54% alpha=255 (the cross-shaped paper net) and 46% alpha=0 (transparent \'97 everything outside the paper).\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The viewer defines extension/corner panels using the SVG viewBox edges as outer bounds (e.g. 
\f2\fs26 top-ext
\f0\fs24  runs from y=0 to y=OY1=671). But the actual paper silhouette in those panels is a smaller, irregular shape (a tab with rounded shoulders), not the full rectangle.\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Where the front face is alpha=0, 
\f2\fs26 alphaTest: 0.1
\f0\fs24  discards the texture pixel \'97 so nothing renders on the front. But each slab still has its cream 
\f1\b edge strips
\f0\b0  around the perimeter. From the camera angle (slightly above the page), those cream edge strips trace visible "ghost rectangles" exactly where you see the white outlines below the c-tab, around the corners, etc.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 So visually you see the paper net in correct position, plus 4 + 4 cream rectangles outlining empty regions where slabs extend past the paper.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Yes \'97 the SVG can drive everything, and that's the cleaner path.
\f0\b0  Two distinct wins from doing it:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fold-valley paths drive the panel constants.
\f0\b0  The SVG already has all 8 fold lines as 
\f2\fs26 <path>
\f0\fs24  elements inside 
\f2\fs26 <g id="folds-valley">
\f0\fs24 . Parse those, derive BX1/BX2/BY1/BY2/OX1/OX2/OY1/OY2 automatically. Generalizes to every piece.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Alpha silhouette tightens the panel slabs.
\f0\b0  For each fold-bounded region, compute the alpha-bbox of the actual paper inside it. Use that as the slab dimensions instead of the SVG viewBox edge. The cream-edge ghost rectangles disappear because the slab now matches the paper.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 Two ways to get there, with different scope:Locked in. Let me create tasks and start computing the alpha-bbox panel sizes.Let me refine the crop. The simple alpha-bbox grows top-ext/bot-ext past the wall width and only crops left-ext/right-ext meaningfully \'97 that won't kill the bottom outline artifact. Let me find the largest rectangle fully inside the paper (the "neck" of each tab) and treat the narrowing tip as a tighter sub-rectangle.
\f1\b Found it.
\f0\b0  The PNG has a 1-pixel-wide all-white opaque border row at the very top and bottom (and corner pixels on left/right). Look:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
