Alan:\
regarding the white border - i wasn't complaining about the white border from the beginning, that was you.\
The pieces are human drawn and human edited, so they may have inconsistently some white first or some "ink" from the line drawing, depending on how precisely it's cut at that moment. Do not build in a plan to manually remove a strip of white. Instead, tell me why it is sampling that, does it need to be that color (could it be a constant/defined color instead) and does it matter once the scanned image is rendering correctly anyway?\
I'd like to prioritize refactoring to pull from the SVG. I think that needs to get settled first then build up from there.\
\'97\'97\'97\'97\
Claude:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 You're right \'97 I jumped from "I noticed something" to "and I should fix it" without checking with you, and the fix would have been the wrong move anyway. Removing it would scrub real artifact from a hand-drawn, hand-cut piece. Striking that off the plan.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Why is the slab sampling that strip?
\f0\b0  The slab geometry for 
\f2\fs26 top-ext
\f0\fs24  runs from svg-y=0 (the very top of the viewBox) down to svg-y=OY1=671 (the fold line). The UV mapping is straight-through: outer edge of slab 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  outer edge of texture (UV v=1.0, which is PNG row 0). So the slab is sampling there 
\f4\i because we told it to extend that far
\f0\i0 . The color sitting at that texture row is incidental \'97 it could be opaque white (export artifact), cream paper, or a stray ink stroke from the human edit, and the slab renders whatever it finds. The current code makes no demand about what color is there.\

\f1\b Could it be a constant color instead?
\f0\b0  Two distinct surfaces are involved:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f1\b edge ribbons
\f0\b0  that wrap the slab perimeter (modeling 1mm of cardstock cross-section) already are a constant \'97 
\f2\fs26 edgeMat
\f0\fs24  in cream 
\f2\fs26 0xF5EDD6
\f0\fs24 . That part is fine; it's never sampling the texture.\
\ls8\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f1\b outer edge of the front face
\f0\b0  is the texture sample. We could force a constant there, but I don't think we want to \'97 once the slab is sized to where the paper actually ends, that outer-edge sample IS the paper's natural edge, ink-stains and rough cuts and all. That's higher fidelity than blanking it to cream.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \strokec2 Does it matter once the scan renders correctly?
\f0\b0  No. The outline rectangles disappear by construction. The "white border" diagnosis is just a symptom of slabs being bigger than the paper inside them.\
So all roads point to the same root cause: 
\f1\b slab silhouette \uc0\u8800  paper silhouette
\f0\b0 . Fixing that is what the SVG refactor unlocks.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
