\f1\b \cf0 \strokec2 On texture content
\f0\b0  \'97 now that we've settled on polygon-shaped slabs, here's my read on the three options:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Rasterize whole SVG to a canvas as the texture.
\f0\b0  Render 
\f2\fs26 inbox/069.svg
\f0\fs24  (Background image + folds-valley dashed lines + marks ellipses + axles) into a canvas at, say, 2048px wide. Use that as the texture. What you see in 3D = what the SVG was authored to look like. Simplest pipeline, generalizes across pieces with no per-layer code. The fold dashes and tab labels you see in the screenshot would render exactly that way. Texture clarity bound by canvas resolution.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Scan only as texture, render fold/mark/axle layers as separate 3D geometry.
\f0\b0  Rasterize just the 
\f2\fs26 <image>
\f0\fs24  for the texture; render fold-valley paths as 3D dashed lines (
\f2\fs26 LineDashedMaterial
\f0\fs24 ), marks as colored disks, axles as a sphere + axis line (matches your "perfect" experimental viewer). More code, more decisions (line color, dash spacing, marker size), but each layer becomes inspectable independently \'97 toggleable, clickable for 
\f2\fs26 tab-a
\f0\fs24  
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  "glues to landing-a." Future-friendly for the assembly graph.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Both \'97 scan-only texture + optional 3D overlays.
\f0\b0  Texture is just the scan; UI checkboxes show/hide 3D fold lines / marks / axles on top. Heaviest to build. You eventually want this for inspection but it's not minimal-viable.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 A practical detail that nudges between these: with polygon-shaped slabs, the texture sample at any folded surface point is the scan content at that exact authored position. The fold-valley dashes drawn in the SVG live IN the texture (option 1) or AS geometry on the BASE (option 2). Option 1 means the dashes fold along with the wall \'97 you see them on the inside surface of a folded box wall, exactly where the paper has them. Option 2 means the dashes only show on the BASE in 3D space, which doesn't make physical sense once a wall has folded up. So option 1 is more faithful to the actual paper.\
