\f1\b \cf0 Reframing what we know:
\f0\b0 \
The scan PNG already contains everything that's 
\f4\i printed on the paper
\f0\i0 : the dashed fold lines, the tab labels (a, b, c, \'85), the 
\f2\fs26 +
\f0\fs24  center, the silhouette. That's what the user assembling the clock would see on the page. The SVG's 
\f2\fs26 folds-valley
\f0\fs24  / 
\f2\fs26 marks
\f0\fs24  / 
\f2\fs26 axles
\f0\fs24  layers are metadata Z added on top \'97 the bright green fold paths are vector tracings of where the scan's dashed lines are, the yellow tab ellipses are positioned over where the printed dots are, and so on.\
So a render that "rasterizes the whole SVG" would paint bright green over already-printed dashed lines, yellow over already-printed dots, and magenta over the printed 
\f2\fs26 +
\f0\fs24 . That's audit-mode visualization, not faithful render. We probably don't want that as the default.\

\f1\b Where that leaves us:
\f0\b0 \
The base render wants to be 
\f1\b scan only
\f0\b0  \'97 extract just the 
\f2\fs26 <image>
\f0\fs24  from the SVG, rasterize it (or use it directly, since 069's transform is uniform scale), use as texture. That gives you the faithful "this is what the paper looks like" view, and the printed fold dashes / tab labels appear naturally because they're already in the scan.\
The SVG layers stay valuable for 
\f1\b inspection
\f0\b0 , but as 3D geometry overlays you can toggle on:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Axle pivot
\f0\b0  \'97 an actual 3D sphere + vertical axis line at the 
\f2\fs26 anchor-pivot
\f0\fs24  position. This one is genuinely useful in 3D because it's a 
\f4\i position
\f0\i0 , not a printed mark. You want to see it from any orbit angle, including through occluding folded walls. Worth shipping in the first cut.\
\ls13\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fold lines
\f0\b0  \'97 
\f2\fs26 folds-valley
\f0\fs24  as 3D lines in the original authoring color. Lower utility once the scan already shows the dashes; mostly only useful when you suspect a placement bug in the SVG.\
\ls13\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Mark ellipses
\f0\b0  \'97 
\f2\fs26 tab-a
\f0\fs24 \'85
\f2\fs26 tab-g
\f0\fs24 , 
\f2\fs26 landing-a
\f0\fs24 \'85, etc. as 3D colored disks. Useful when wiring up the assembly graph in M4 (knowing which tab glues to which landing on which adjacent piece).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 A small but real complexity: marks and fold lines need to be assigned to a panel so they follow that panel through the fold animation. Marks are easy (each ellipse falls inside exactly one panel's region). Fold lines are slightly trickier \'97 fold-valley paths sit 
\f4\i along
\f0\i0  hinge axes, between two panels; we'd need to pick which panel they "belong to" or render them only in flat state.\
My suggestion: ship the viewer with 
\f1\b scan-only texture, 3D pivot sphere always visible, fold-line and mark overlays deferred
\f0\b0 . That's the minimum that gets you a faithful render plus the one inspection element that's genuinely useful in 3D. Add fold/mark overlays in a follow-up once we feel the gap.\
